    <header>
        <div class="container">
            <h1>Privacy Act Information</h1>
            <p>Understanding your rights and responsibilities under privacy legislation</p>
        </div>
    </header>
    
    <div class="container">
        <div class="card card-highlight">
            <h2>Key Principles Overview</h2>
            <p>The Privacy Act establishes fundamental principles that organizations must follow when handling personal information. These principles ensure proper collection, storage, use, and disclosure of personal data.</p>
        </div>
        <nav>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/"><i class="fas fa-home"></i> Home</a></li>
          <li><a href="/introduction" class="active"><i class="fas fa-info-circle"></i> Introduction</a></li>
          <li><a href="/challenges"><i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> Challenges</a></li>
          <li><a href="/privacy-act"><i class="fas fa-gavel"></i> Privacy Act</a></li>
          <li><a href="/gdpr"><i class="fas fa-globe-europe"></i> GDPR</a></li>
          <li><a href="/conclusion"><i class="fas fa-flag-checkered"></i> Conclusion</a></li>
        </ul>
      </nav>
        
        <div class="two-column">
            <div>
                <div class="principle-box">
                    <h3>Principle 5: Storage and Security of Information</h3>
                    <p>Organizations must implement reasonable safeguards to prevent loss, misuse, or disclosure of personal information.</p>
                    
                    <ul class="feature-list">
                        <li>Requires protection against unauthorized access</li>
                        <li>Mandates breach notification within 72 hours for serious incidents</li>
                        <li>Applies to all forms of data storage (digital and physical)</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p><strong>Key Requirement:</strong> Serious privacy breaches must be reported to the Privacy Commissioner within 72 hours.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="principle-box">
                    <h3>Principle 6: Access to Personal Information</h3>
                    <p>Individuals have the right to access their personal information held by organizations.</p>
                    
                    <ul class="feature-list">
                        <li>Verify what information is being collected</li>
                        <li>Understand how the information is being used</li>
                        <li>Request corrections to inaccurate information</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p><strong>Note:</strong> Access rights apply only to one's own information unless written consent is provided for others.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <div>
                <div class="principle-box">
                    <h3>Principle 9: Retention of Personal Information</h3>
                    <p>Organizations should only keep personal information as long as necessary for lawful purposes.</p>
                    
                    <ul class="feature-list">
                        <li>No minimum retention periods specified</li>
                        <li>Must comply with other relevant legislation</li>
                        <li>Requires clear retention policies</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <h4>Specific Retention Requirements:</h4>
                    <ul class="feature-list">
                        <li><strong>Medical records:</strong> 10 years from last service (Health Information Regulations 1996)</li>
                        <li><strong>Employee records:</strong> Varies by information type and relevant laws</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                
                <div class="case-study">
                    <h4>Case Study: Recruitment Agency Profile Retention</h4>
                    <p>A recruitment agency failed to completely remove a former client's online profile after request. While they removed name and photo, other identifying information remained accessible.</p>
                    <p><strong>Resolution:</strong> The agency ultimately removed all profile information after investigation confirmed Principle 9 violation.</p>
                    <p><strong>Lesson:</strong> Partial removal may not satisfy privacy obligations if information remains identifiable.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card">
            <h2>Key Privacy Laws</h2>
            
            <h3>For Individuals: Know Your Rights</h3>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li><strong>GDPR (EU):</strong> Access, correct, delete data; withdraw consent</li>
                <li><strong>CCPA (California):</strong> Opt-out of data sales; request collection details</li>
                <li><strong>PIPL (China):</strong> Clear consent required for sensitive data</li>
                <li><strong>NZ Privacy Act:</strong> Breach notifications; information access rights</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>For Organizations: Compliance Essentials</h3>
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>Invest in data protection measures (encryption, anonymization)</li>
                <li>Potential fines up to 4% of global revenue (GDPR)</li>
                <li>Privacy compliance builds customer trust and brand loyalty</li>
                <li>Requires ongoing monitoring and policy updates</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        
        <div class="two-column">
            <div class="card">
                <h2>Data Protection Mechanisms</h2>
                
                <h3>Legal Frameworks</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>GDPR (EU data protection standards)</li>
                    <li>CCPA (California consumer rights)</li>
                    <li>HIPAA (US health information)</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h3>Technical Solutions</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Encryption (AES, homomorphic)</li>
                    <li>Differential privacy techniques</li>
                    <li>Access control systems (RBAC)</li>
                    <li>Blockchain for decentralized control</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h3>Organizational Measures</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Privacy-by-design principles</li>
                    <li>Data Protection Officers (DPOs)</li>
                    <li>Regular staff training</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="card">
                <h2>Security Best Practices</h2>
                
                <h3>For Individuals</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Use security tools (antivirus, firewalls)</li>
                    <li>Practice safe online behavior</li>
                    <li>Enable multi-factor authentication</li>
                    <li>Maintain digital hygiene (clearing cache, backups)</li>
                    <li>Stay informed about threats</li>
                </ul>
                
                <h3>For Organizations</h3>
                <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>Implement robust access controls (RBAC, MFA)</li>
                    <li>Encrypt data at rest and in transit</li>
                    <li>Regular security training and phishing tests</li>
                    <li>Follow 3-2-1 backup rule</li>
                    <li>Conduct regular security audits</li>
                    <li>Develop incident response plans</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="card">
            <h2>Access Request Handling (Principle 6)</h2>
            <p>Organizations must follow specific protocols when responding to personal information access requests:</p>
            
            <ul class="feature-list">
                <li>Only the individual or authorized representative can submit requests</li>
                <li>Urgent requests may receive priority handling</li>
                <li>Organizations must assist requestors in making requests</li>
                <li>Requests must be transferred to correct agency within 10 working days if not held</li>
                <li>Response required within 20 working days (extensions possible for complex cases)</li>
                <li>Access may be refused for specific justified reasons (must inform requestor of complaint rights)</li>
                <li>Information must be provided in preferred format when practical</li>
            </ul>
            
            <h3>Valid Reasons for Refusal</h3>
            <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.5rem;">
                <span class="badge">Endangering life/safety</span>
                <span class="badge">Confidential evaluative material</span>
                <span class="badge">National security</span>
                <span class="badge">Trade secrets</span>
                <span class="badge">Non-existent information</span>
                <span class="badge">Frivolous requests</span>
            </div>
